Theorem 1. [9] In a (k, n)-torus, given any two nodes s and d, we can Ô¨Ånd 2n mutually
node-disjoint paths s ‚ùÄ d of lengths at most n k/2 + 1 in O(n3 ) time.

3

Proposed algorithm

In this section, we describe the algorithm to solve the container problem for two distinct nodes
s and d in a T CC(k, n). Because each node in a T CC(k, 1) has only two neighbour nodes, it is
impossible to Ô¨Ånd three disjoint paths. Therefore, we assume that n ‚â• 2. In addition, we use
an algorithm that solves the container problem in an n-dimensional torus to Ô¨Ånd 2n mutually
node-disjoint paths. If k = 2, then each node in the torus has only n neighbour nodes. Hence,
it is also impossible to Ô¨Ånd 2n paths. Therefore, we assume that k ‚â• 3.
According to the relative positions of s = (c(s), ps ) and d = (c(d), pd ), we divide the
algorithm into four cases as follows; in addition, the pseudo-code of the algorithm is given in
Algorithms 1 and 2.

3.1

Case 1

In this subsection, we discuss the case where d ‚àà C(s) and d = n1 (s). The three mutually
disjoint paths are obtained in two steps as follows.
Step 1 In the cycle C(s), construct two disjoint paths from s to d.
Step 2 Construct the path s ‚Üí n3 (s) ‚Üí n1 (n3 (s)) ‚Üí n3 (n1 (n3 (s))) ‚Üí . . . ‚Üí n3 (d) ‚Üí d.
See Figure 2.

